'''Billie Jo Spears''' (born '''Billie Jean Moore'''; January 14, 1938 – December 14, 2011)<ref name="NY Times">{{cite news |last1=Friskics-Warren |first1=Bill |title=Billie Jo Spears, Country Singer, Dies at 73 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/17/arts/music/billie-jo-spears-country-singer-dies-at-73.html |access-date=February 4, 2023 |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 17, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Whitburn |first1=Joel |title=Joel Whitburn's Top Country Songs: 1944-2005 |date=2005 |publisher=Record Research |isbn=978-0898201659 |page=358}}</ref> was an American [[country music]] singer. She was known for a series of [[Single (music)|singles]] whose characters often represented women in assertive positions. Among these recordings was a song about sexual harassment ("[[Mr. Walker, It's All Over]]"), and a song about rekindling sexual desire ("[[Blanket on the Ground]])".

Spears was raised in a working-class Texas family. She made her first recording at age 13 on the [[Abbott Records|Abbott]] label. Singer–songwriter [[Jack Rhodes]] discovered her early music and helped her secure a professional partnership with producer Kelso Herston. Under Herston's production, she had her first top-ten song with 1969's "Mr. Walker, It's All Over" (issued on [[Capitol Records]]). Several follow-up releases were not successful, and after recovering from a vocal setback she returned to United Artists. Her second release was 1975's "Blanket on the Ground", which topped the American country chart and became a commercial [[Pop music|pop]] success in several countries.

Spears followed with several more American top ten and top 20 country songs like "[[What I've Got in Mind]]", "[[Misty Blue]]", "[[If You Want Me (song)|If You Want Me]]", "[['57 Chevrolet (song)|'57 Chevrolet]]" and a cover of "[[I Will Survive]]". Spears continued to have success overseas, particularly in the United Kingdom where she had several more top 40 songs. In 1981, Spears left United Artists (now [[Liberty Records|Liberty]]) and recorded several albums with British labels during the 1980's and 90's. She also continued to tour throughout, most notably in the United Kingdom. Meanwhile, Spears married and divorced five times between the 1960's and 90's. In 2011, Spears died of cancer at age 73.

==Early life==
Billie Jean Moore was born in [[Beaumont, Texas]] and was one of six children.<ref name="Independent">{{cite news|title=Billie Jo Spears: Country singer who scored her biggest hit with|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/billie-jo-spears-country-singer-who-scored-her-biggest-hit-with-blanket-on-the-ground-6277683.html|work=The Independent|date=December 16, 2011}}</ref> Her father was a truck driver, while her mother worked as a shipyard welder and waitress.<ref name="Independent"/><ref name="Music Row">{{cite magazine |last1=Oermann |first1=Robert K. |title=Billie Jo Spears Passes |magazine=Music Row |date=December 14, 2011 |url=https://musicrow.com/2011/12/billie-jo-spears-passes/ |access-date=January 4, 2023}}</ref> Moore was usually called "BJ" during her childhood and the nickname stuck throughout her adult life.<ref name="Beaumont Enterprise">{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Julie |title=Vidor country singer Billie Jo Spears remembered as feisty star |url=https://www.beaumontenterprise.com/news/article/Vidor-country-singer-Billie-Jo-Spears-remembered-2405128.php |access-date=February 4, 2023 |work=[[The Beaumont Enterprise]] |date=December 15, 2011}}</ref> She was routinely exposed to country music throughout her childhood.<ref name="UA Country Artists">{{cite magazine |title=UA Country Artists: Billie Jo Spears |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=October 9, 1976 |volume=88 |issue=41 |page=UA-11 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ySQEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billie+jo+spears+raised+in+a+musical+family&pg=PT49 |access-date=February 4, 2023}}</ref> Her mother spent some of her free time performing as a guitarist in a [[western swing]] band called the Light Crust Doughboys.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=272}}

Moore's sister Betty first had aspirations of becoming a country artist and even signed a recording contract, but she chose a domestic life over a professional career.<ref name="Independent"/> Moore began singing professionally at age 13. She was discovered by songwriter [[Jack Rhodes]], who helped her land an appearance on the ''[[Louisiana Hayride]]'' television program. This brought Moore to the attention of the [[Abbott Records|Abbott]] label.<ref name="Guardian">{{cite news |last1=Russell |first1=Tony |title=Billie Jo Spears Obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/dec/15/billie-jo-spears |access-date=February 4, 2023 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=December 15, 2011}}</ref> In 1953, the company released her first single while she was still a teenager titled "Too Old for Toys, Too Young for Boys". The track was issued under the name "Billie Jo Moore".<ref name="Moore">{{cite journal |last1=Moore |first1=Billie Jo |title="Too Young for Toys, Too Young for Boys"/"I Dess I Dotta Doe" (Single Information) |journal=[[Abbott Records]] |date=September 1953}}</ref> According to the ''Encyclopedia of Music in the 20th Century'', the record brought in an estimated $4,200.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Stacey |editor1-first=Lee |editor2-last=Henderson |editor2-first=Lol |title=Encyclopedia of Music in the 20th Century |date=2014 |publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]] |isbn=978-1135929534}}</ref> However, a separate statement from ''[[The Independent]]'' claimed that the record only brought Moore $2000.<ref name="Independent"/>

Moore graduated from Beaumont's [[French High School]] in 1955.<ref name="Beaumont Enterprise"/> Upon graduating, she worked a series of jobs outside the music industry.<ref name="UA Country Artists"/> This included working as a carhop for four years at Neva's, a restaurant near her hometown.<ref name="Beaumont Enterprise"/> She also held a position as a clerical worker for the Beaumont Bag and Burlap Company.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=272}} Meanwhile, Jack Rhodes persuaded Moore to pursue a career as a country music artist.<ref name="UA Country Artists"/> In 1964, she moved to [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref name="Independent"/><ref name="NY Times"/> During this period, she changed her professional name to "Billie Jo Spears".<ref name="Beaumont Enterprise"/>

==Career==
===1964–1973: Initial success===
Spears tried to find a recording contract after moving to Nashville. She first made several [[Demo (music)|demonstration records]] with producer [[Pete Drake]]. In 1964, she secured a recording deal with [[United Artists Records]].<ref name="Allmusic">{{cite web |last1=Huey |first1=Steve |title=Billie Jo Spears Biography |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/billie-jo-spears-mn0000081926/biography |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=February 5, 2023}}</ref> She cut several singles that were issued by United Artists but failed to become successful. Her producer at the time was Kelso Herston, who would move to [[Capitol Records]]. Believing in her musical abilities, he helped her switch to Capitol in 1968.<ref name="Allmusic"/><ref name="Country Music People">{{cite magazine |last1=Cackett |first1=Alan |title=Billie Jo Spears |magazine=Country Music People Magazine |date=November 1978 |volume=9 |issue=11}}</ref> Spears's first single for the label was the song "[[Harper Valley PTA]]".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Spears |first1=Billie Jo |title="[[Harper Valley PTA|The Harper Valley PTA]]"/"Home-Loving Man" (Single Information) |journal=[[United Artists Records]] |date=August 1968 |id=2279}}</ref> Released at the same time was a competing version by [[Jeannie C. Riley]] which became the commercially successful version.<ref name="Vidor">{{cite web |title=Billie Jo Spears |url=https://www.cityofvidor.com/billie-jo-spears |website=[[Vidor, Texas|City of Vidor]] |access-date=5 February 2023}}</ref> Spears's next single, "He's Got More Love on His Little Finger", became her first to make the American ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' country chart.<ref name="Country Songs">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944 to 2008|publisher=Record Research, Inc.|year=2008|isbn=978-0-89820-177-2}}</ref> It was followed later in the year by her debut studio album titled ''[[The Voice of Billie Jo Spears]]''.<ref name="Country Music People"/>

Spears' next single release was 1969's "[[Mr. Walker, It's All Over]]". Its musical style and lyrical themes were said to resemble that of "Harper Valley PTA".<ref name="Guardian"/><ref name="Country Music People"/> The song told the story of a [[New York City]] secretary who confronts her boss after facing [[sexual harassment]] in the work place.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=271}} The song became Spears's commercial breakout, reaching the top five of the ''Billboard'' [[Hot Country Songs]] chart,<ref name="Country Songs"/> the top 80 of the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name="Pop Songs">{{cite book |last1=Whitburn |first1=Joel |title=Joel Whitburn, Top Pop Singles 1955-1999 |date=2000 |publisher=Record Research |location=Menomonee Falls, WI |page=various}}</ref> and the top ten of the Canadian ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Country Tracks survey.<ref name="RPM Country Songs">{{cite magazine|title=Search results for "Billie Jo Spears" under Top singles|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=a36pt38kvv478nt2gn80bh1857&q1=Billie+Jo+Spears&q2=Top+Singles&interval=20|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120730223433/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=a36pt38kvv478nt2gn80bh1857&q1=Billie+Jo+Spears&q2=Top+Singles&interval=20|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 30, 2012|magazine=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|accessdate=January 7, 2012}}</ref> Capitol then issued Spears's [[Mr. Walker, It's All Over!|second studio album of the same name]], which reached the ''Billboard'' [[Top Country Albums]] top 30.<ref name="Billboard Albums">{{cite book |last1=Whitburn |first1=Joel |title=Joel Whitburn's Top Country Albums: 1967-1997 |date=1997 |publisher=Record Research Inc. |isbn=0898201241}}</ref> The disc featured several new recordings that followed similar storylines to her top ten single and included a cover of [[Tammy Wynette]]'s "[[Stand by Your Man]]".<ref name="Mr Walker">{{cite journal |last1=Spears |first1=Billie Jo |title=''Mr. Walker, It's All Over!'' (Disc Information) |journal=[[Capitol Records]] |date=May 1969 |id=ST-224 (LP); ST-8-0224 (Club Edition)}}</ref>

[[File:Billie Jo Spears--1972.jpg|thumb|left|Billie Jo Spears in a magazine advertisement for her 1972 single, "Souvenirs and California Memories".]]
Capitol released several follow-up singles by Spears that discussed social issues.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=271-272}}<ref name="Guardian"/> Among them was 1969's "Stepchild", which told the story of a boy who murders his abusive stepfather.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=272}} It only reached number 43 on the ''Billboard'' country chart.<ref name="Country Songs"/> Another follow-up single was 1970's "[[Marty Gray]]", a song that told the story of a teenage girl who becomes unexpectedly pregnant following a sexual encounter with a high school football player.<ref name="Guardian"/>{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=272}} It reached number 17 on the ''Billboard'' country chart.<ref name="Country Songs"/> Her third Capitol studio album, ''[[Miss Sincerity]]'', was her second to make the Country Albums chart.<ref name="Billboard Albums"/>

With her new success, Spears toured in the United Kingdom for the first time as part of the "Capitol Country Caravan". She would later find her greatest success overseas.<ref name="Independent"/> Critics and writers also took notice of Spears's music for the first time. Alan Cackett of ''Country Music People'' called her "a fine singer" with "emotional styling".<ref name="Country Music People"/> In reviewing her second album, [[AllMusic]]'s Richie Unterberger praised Spears's assertive vocal style and song choices: "It's a quite strong set of material, hewing to the gutsier side of late-'60s country-pop, with Spears proving herself as one of the tougher, harder-edged, commercial country singers of the era."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Unterberger |first1=Richie |title=''Mr. Walker, It's All Over!'': Billie Jo Spears: Songs, reviews, credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/mr-walker-its-all-over%21-mw0001480834 |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=February 5, 2023}}</ref>

In 1970, Spears began working alongside Capitol producer [[George Richey]]. He attempted to move her music in an [[Pop music|orchestrated pop]] direction.<ref name="Country Music People"/> Studio albums like ''With Love, Billie Jo Spears'' (1970) and ''[[Country Girl (Billie Jo Spears album)|Country Girl]]'' (1971) featured remakes of [[Johnny Bond]]'s "Your Old Love Letters" and [[Cole Porter]]'s "[[True Love (Cole Porter song)|True Love]]".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Spears |first1=Billie Jo |title=''Country Girl'' (Disc Information) |journal=[[Capitol Records]] |date=August 1970 |id=ST-560}}</ref><ref name="With Love">{{cite journal |last1=Spears |first1=Billie Jo |title=''With Love, Billie Jo Spears'' (Disc Information) |journal=[[Capitol Records]] |date=March 1970 |id=ST-454}}</ref> Through 1971, the singles "[[I Stayed Long Enough]]" and "[[It Could 'A Been Me]]" made the ''Billboard'' country top 40.<ref name="Country Songs"/> When her next releases failed to prove successful, Capitol Records dropped Spears from their roster.<ref name="Country Music People"/> Following her departure, Spears was forced to have vocal chord surgery which set her career back as well. After recovering, she returned on the independent Brite Star and Cutlass labels. However, the label made poor business choices. "Everyone involved with them should be behind bars, and some of them are," she later commented.<ref name="Independent"/>

===1974–1981: Comeback, international success and peak years===
In 1974, Spears returned to United Artists Records. She was signed by producer [[Larry Butler (producer)|Larry Butler]], who was growing his country roster at the label.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=356}}<ref name="Independent"/> Her first United Artists release was a remake of [[Bobby Goldsboro]]'s "[[See the Funny Little Clown]]". It failed to become successful and Spears began looking for her next hit.<ref name="Country Music People"/> Butler brought Spears to the attention of a new song penned by [[Roger Bowling (songwriter)|Roger Bowling]] called "[[Blanket on the Ground]]".<ref name="Independent"/> It had been previously rejected by several producers who thought the song's sexual themes were too controversial.<ref name="Independent"/> "It sounded like a cheating song, and the public don't think girls should sing cheating songs!" she commented.<ref name="Larkin">{{cite book |last1=Larkin |first1=Colin |title=The Encyclopedia of Popular Music |date=2007 |publisher=[[Omnibus Press]] |isbn=978-0857125958 |page=1905}}</ref> "Blanket on the Ground" reached number one on the ''Billboard'' country chart,<ref name="Country Songs"/> number 78 on the Hot 100<ref name="Pop Songs"/> and number two on the ''RPM'' country chart.<ref name="RPM Country Songs"/> It also became an international crossover success,<ref name="Larkin"/> reaching number six in the United Kingdom<ref name="UK">{{cite web |title=Billi Jo Spears: Official full chart history: Albums |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/15372/billie-jo-spears/ |website=[[Official Charts Company]] |access-date=January 26, 2023}}</ref> number 11 in Ireland<ref name="Irish Songs">{{cite web |title=The Irish Charts: Billie Jo Spears |url=http://irishcharts.ie/search/placement |website=irishcharts.ne |access-date=January 28, 2023}}</ref> among other countries.<ref name="Larkin"/>

Spears's first United Artists album of the [[Blanket on the Ground (album)|same name]] reached the top five of the ''Billboard'' country chart in 1975.<ref name="Rough Guide">{{cite book|last1=Wolff|first1=Kurt|title=Country Music: The Rough Guide|date=2000|publisher=Penguin Books|location=London|isbn=1-85828-534-8 |page=454}}</ref> It became a best-selling album in the United Kingdom,<ref>{{cite web |title=WHAT I'VE GOT IN MIND by Billie Jo Spears sales and awards |url=https://bestsellingalbums.org/album/5215 |website=Best Selling Albums.org |access-date=February 11, 2023}}</ref> receiving a "Silver" certification from the [[British Phonographic Industry]].<ref name="BPI">{{cite web |title=''Blanket on the Ground'' (Type Billie Jo Spears in the "Search BPI Awards" field and then press Enter) |url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/brit-certified/ |website=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |access-date=February 11, 2023}}</ref> The comeback brought Spears the Top New Female Vocalist accolade from the [[Academy of Country Music Awards]] during this time.<ref name="Rough Guide"/> "It sure is good to be back. I'm a different person now when I'm recording, because I'm also able to present a much better show on my personal appearances," she commented.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=357}} To conclude 1975, Spears had two top 20 North American country singles with "[[Stay Away from the Apple Tree]]" and "[[Silver Wings and Golden Rings]]".<ref name="Country Songs"/><ref name="RPM Country Songs"/>

[[File:Billie Jo Spears--1976.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Billie Jo Spears performing on a music show in 1976.]]
Spears's collaboration with producer Larry Butler continued through the seventies. Butler crafted an up-tempo, [[country pop]] sound that was considered both marketable and dance-able. Many of her most popular singles reflected themes of sexual desire or rekindling loves fading fires.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=356-357}}<ref name="Music Row"/> Her next single was 1976's "[[What I've Got in Mind]]", which also hinted at sexual themes. The single reached the top five of the North American country charts and the top five of the UK pop chart.<ref name="UK"/><ref name="Music Row"/> Her studio LP of the [[What I've Got in Mind (album)|same name]] also reached the Top Country Albums top five and certified silver from the BPI.<ref name="Billboard Albums"/><ref name="BPI"/> The album also spawned a cover of the ballad, "[[Misty Blue]]", which reached the American country top five.<ref name="Country Songs"/><ref name="Country Music People"/> "[[Sing Me an Old Fashioned Song]]" was released to European countries, peaking within United Kingdom top 40 and the top ten in Ireland.<ref name="UK"/><ref name="Irish Songs"/> Her British success later led to multiple appearances at the [[Wembley Arena]], where she became a favorite with crowds for many years.<ref name="Guardian"/> During this period, she also collaborated with [[Del Reeves]] on the album ''By Request''. The disc featured duet recordings by the pair and was released on United Artists in 1976.<ref name="Country Music People"/>

Spears had a string of top ten and top 20 country singles during the later half of the seventies.<ref name="Rough Guide"/> The 1977 releases, "[[Never Did Like Whiskey]]" and "[[I'm Not Easy]]", both made the top 20 of the American country charts. They were included on her 1977 top 40 country LP, ''[[I'm Not Easy (album)|I'm Not Easy]]''.<ref name="Billboard Albums"/><ref name="Country Songs"/> ''I'm Not Easy'' also featured a cover of [[Elvis Presley]]'s "[[Heartbreak Hotel]]",<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Spears |first1=Billie Jo |title=''I'm Not Easy'' (Disc Information) |journal=[[United Artists Records]] |date=November 1976 |id=UA-LA684-G}}</ref> which was intended to be a single. According to the ''Independent'', Spears cancelled the single following the death of Presley because she did not want to "exploit" his passing.<ref name="Independent"/> Instead, the up-tempo "[[If You Want Me (song)|If You Want Me]]" reached the Hot County Songs top ten in 1977.<ref name="Allmusic"/>{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=357}} Through 1978, four of Spears's singles reached the top 20 consecutively: "[[Too Much Is Not Enough (Billie Jo Spears song)|Too Much Is Not Enough]]", "[[Lonely Hearts Club (Billie Jo Spears song)|Lonely Hearts Club]]", "[[I've Got to Go]]" and "[['57 Chevrolet (song)|'57 Chevrolet]]".<ref name="Country Songs"/><ref name="RPM Country Songs"/>

In 1979, United Artists released Spears's cover of [[Gloria Gaynor]]'s [[Disco music|disco]] hit "[[I Will Survive]]". It was a popular recording in the United Kingdom, where it charted on their pop survey.<ref name="UK"/><ref name="UK Number Ones">{{cite book |last1=Kutner |first1=John |last2=Leigh |first2=Spencer |title=1,000 UK Number One Hits |date=2013 |publisher=[[Omnibus Press]] |isbn=978-0-85712-360-2}}</ref> It also reached number 21 on the American country chart and number nine on the Canadian country chart.<ref name="Country Songs"/><ref name="RPM Country Songs"/> "I Will Survive" served as the name for her [[I Will Survive (Billie Jo Spears album)|1979 LP]], which spawned two additional charting singles. Greg Adams of [[AllMusic]] gave the disc a four-star rating and called it "a typically fine effort".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=Greg |title=''I Will Survive'': Billie Jo Spears: Songs, reviews, credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/i-will-survive-mw0000998191 |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=February 12, 2023}}</ref> In 1980, a song about walking away from a failed relationship ("[[Standing Tall (song)|Standing Tall]]"){{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=357}} returned Spears to the top 20 of the American country chart and the top ten of the Canadian country chart.<ref name="Country Songs"/><ref name="RPM Country Songs"/> Her 1981 cover of [[Tammy Wynette]]'s "[[Your Good Girl's Gonna Go Bad (song)|Your Good Girl's Gonna Go Bad]]" was her final top 20 country single.<ref name="Allmusic"/> Spears then departed from United Artists (now Liberty) records.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Morris |first1=Edward |title=Big Label Switch Is On: Labels Alter Lists |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=July 25, 1981 |volume=93 |issue=29 |page=57 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GCUEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billie+jo+spears+leaves+liberty+records+1981&pg=PT80 |access-date=February 19, 2023}}</ref>

===1982–2011: Focus in the United Kingdom and final career years===
In 1982, Spears signed with the United Kingdom-based label Ritz Records. The label received airplay on [[BBC Radio 2]] and Spears was promised to receive airtime there. Her first label single was 1982's "Apologizing Roses".<ref>{{cite magazine |title=U.K.'s Ritz Label Developing Catalog |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=October 9, 1982 |page=52 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7SMEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billie+jo+spears+signs+with+ritz+records+1983&pg=PT87}}</ref> It was included on the Ritz studio album, ''BJ – Billie Jo Spears Today'' (1983). Along with new material, the disc also featured covers of "[[Seven Lonely Days]]" and [[John Anderson (singer)|John Anderson]]'s "[[Swingin' (John Anderson song)|Swingin']]".<ref name="Today">{{cite journal |last1=Spears |first1=Billie |title=''BJ – Billie Jo Spears Today'' (Disc Information) |journal=Ritz Records |date=October 1983 |id=RITZLP-0016 (LP)}}</ref> Spears also collaborated on a duet with Carey Duncan called "I Can Hear Kentucky Calling Me".<ref name="Larkin"/> In 1984, the Premier label (also based in the United Kingdom) released her next studio album titled ''We Just Came Apart at the Dreams''. It featured new recordings, along with covers of [[Rosanne Cash]]'s "[[Ain't No Money]]" and [[Don Gibson]]'s "[[Sweet Dreams (Don Gibson song)|Sweet Dreams]]".<ref name="Dreams">{{cite journal |last1=Spears |first1=Billie |title=''We Just Came Apart at the Dreams'' (Disc Information) |journal=Premier |date=1984 |id=PREM-101 (LP); PREMK-101 (Cassette)}}</ref> Its title track was issued as a single in 1983.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Spears |first1=Billie Jo |title="We Just Came Apart at the Dreams"/"Can't Change My Heart" (Single Information) |journal=Premier Records |date=1983 |id=PS-1003}}</ref> Spears's final chart appearance in the United States was a cover of "[[Midnight Blue (Melissa Manchester song)|Midnight Blue]]", which reached the ''Billboard'' country songs top 40 in 1984.<ref name="Country Songs"/> A 1986 joint venture between [[MCA Records|MCA]]/[[Dot Records|Dot]] resulted in an eponymous studio project.<ref name="MCA Dot">{{cite journal |last1=Spears |first1=Billie |title=''Billie Jo Spears'' (Disc Information) |journal=Dot Records/MCA Records |date=May 1986 |id=MCA-39071 (LP); MCAC-39071 (Cassette)}}</ref>

In 1991, Broadland International released Spears's next studio project titled ''[[Unmistakably]]''. The disc contained ten songs, most of which were new recordings.<ref name="Unmistakably">{{cite journal |last1=Spears |first1=Billie |title=''Unmistakably'' (Disc Information) |journal=Broadland International Records |date=1991 |id=ET-CD194 (Compact disc)}}</ref> Its only single was the track "One Smokey Rose", which originally reached the top ten on the Canadian country chart for [[Anita Perras]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Spears |first1=Billie Jo |title="One Smokey Rose"/"One Smokey Rose" (Single Information) |journal=Broadland International |date=1991 |id=BR1-0191}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.8616&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=a4hef7njapfde3pfpd9t8nkb41|title=RPM Country Tracks for June 11, 1988|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|accessdate=September 23, 2010}}</ref> Spears also recorded several cuts at Broadland for an intended duets project, which never came to be. "The album never got finished and I don't know what happened to the money. It's pathetic and I'm very disappointed." she told journalist Spencer Leigh.<ref name="Independent"/> In 1996, Spears returned with the studio album ''Outlaw Woman''.<ref name="Larkin"/> The disc was co-produced by Spears and was released in the United Kingdom by [[Carlton Records]].<ref name="Outlaw Woman">{{cite journal |last1=Spears |first1=Billie |title=''Outlaw Woman'' (Disc Information) |journal=[[Carlton Records]] |date=1996 |id=30363-00092 (Compact disc)}}</ref> Spears also recorded many of her most-popular songs for several low budget albums.<ref name="Larkin"/> Among them was a 1998 studio project distributed by [[K-tel]].<ref name="K-tel">{{cite journal |last1=Spears |first1=Billie Jo |title=''The Best of Billie Jo Spears: New Recordings of Her Greatest Hits...and More...'' (Disc Information) |journal=[[K-tel]] |date=1998 |id=ECD-3400 (CD)}}</ref>

In the final years of her career, Spears continued to perform on a regular basis. Because of her notable following in the United Kingdom, Spears did most of her concert engagements there.<ref name="Allmusic"/> She would complete over 400 concerts and engagements in the United Kingdom during her lifetime. Spears hoped to record a live album at the [[Pavilion Theatre (Glasgow)|Pavilion Theatre]] in Scotland, but never got around to doing so.<ref name="Independent"/> Shortly before her passing, Spears performed regularly with Irish country artist, [[Philomena Begley]]. This included a tour in both 2010 and 2011.<ref>{{cite news |title=Billie Joe and Philomena team up again at Riverside |url=https://www.northernirelandworld.com/arts-and-culture/billie-joe-and-philomena-team-up-again-at-riverside-2833812 |access-date=February 20, 2023 |work=[[National World|Northern Ireland World]] |date=March 4, 2010}}</ref><ref name="Guardian"/>

==Artistry==
Spears's musical style was rooted in the country genre.<ref name="Rough Guide"/><ref name="Allmusic"/>{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=356-357}} Specifically, her early Capitol recordings embedded aspects of traditional country. Writers Mary A. Bufwack and Robert K. Oermann found that her sixties-era recordings had a "diminutive honky-tonker" style{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=271}} while Richie Unterberger of AllMusic found the same selections to have "harder edge" compared to other female artists.<ref name="Mr Walker"/> Many writers found that Spears's United Artists/Liberty recordings shifted towards [[country pop]] and [[Disco|country disco]].<ref name="Music Row"/> Author Kurt Wolff disagreed in his book ''Country Music: The Rough Guide'': "Though Billie Jo Spears had her biggest hits during the 1970s, she was far more earthy and grounded than most singers passing for 'country' during the decade."<ref name="Rough Guide"/>

Bufwack and Oermann found that her late seventies music was "some of the most distinctive pop-country fusion discs of the day."{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=356-357}} Stephen L. Betts of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' found that Spears also had elements of country disco, highlighting 1979's "I Will Survive" in the article ''Country Disco: 15 Great, Wild and WTF Songs''. "With the familiar piano opening by Hargus "Pig" Robbins and backing vocals from the Jordanaires, the Grammy-nominated country-meets-western-meets-Studio 54 concoction remains deliciously odd and totally irresistible," he concluded.<ref name="Rolling Stone">{{cite magazine |last1=Betts |first1=Stephen L. |last2=McKenna |first2=Brittney |last3=Kelly |first3=Hunter |title=Country Disco: 15 Great, Wild and WTF Songs |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=May 14, 2018 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country-lists/country-disco-15-great-wild-and-wtf-songs-629519/billie-jo-spears-i-will-survive-629601/ |access-date=February 20, 2023}}</ref>

Writers and critics also highlighted the blues-influenced style of Spears's vocal delivery. AllMusic's Steve Huey called her "a perfect torch balladeer" with a "sultry, bluesy voice".<ref name="Allmusic"/> In an AllMusic review of a compilation album, Stephen Cook called Spears's vocals "smoky and sensual".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cook |first1=Stephen |title=''The Best of Billie Jo Spears'': Billie Jo Spears |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-best-of-billie-jo-spears-capitol-1979--mw0001169376 |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=February 20, 2023}}</ref>  Music writers also noticed Spears's characteristic [[twang]] in her vocal performances. Bufwack and Oermann commented that she had a "Texas accent as thick as salsa and twice as tangy."{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=271}} Kurt Wolff commented, "Her voice was strong and confident sort of a combination of [[Loretta Lynn]] twang and the swampy soul of [[Bobbie Gentry]]."<ref name="Rough Guide"/> Stephen L. Betts described her as a "twangy Texan".<ref name="Rolling Stone"/>

==Legacy==
Writers and journalists have remembered Spears for songs that showed women in strong and assertive positions. Following her death, Bill Friskics-Warren of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote, "Ms. Spears rose to prominence in the late 1960s with a string of up-tempo, socially conscious songs portraying plucky survivors."<ref name="NY Times"/> Mary A. Bufwack and Robert K. Oermann explained in their 2003 book that Spears's choice of material set her apart: "Billie Jo was unusual for a country female of the period in that she recorded hardly any 'victim' material. Almost all of the star's hit ballads are of women leaving, surviving or otherwise asserting themselves."{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=357}}

Spears's music has been recorded by other artists and has been considered influential to other artists. [[Tammy Wynette]] was influenced by Spears's sixties-era United Artists recordings. According to producer Kelso Herston, Wynette studied her singing style by listening to Spears's records in his Nashville office. "I still think that she was influenced some by Billie Jo. She really did like her," he told biographer [[Jimmy McDonough]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=McDonough |first1=Jimmy |title=Tammy Wynette: The Tragic Country Queen |date=2010 |publisher=[[Penguin Group]] |isbn=978-1-101-18995-5 |page=84}}</ref> [[Lorrie Morgan]] knew many of Spear's recordings about assertive women and cut Spears's "Standing Tall" for her 1995 compilation ''[[Reflections: Greatest Hits]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hurst |first1=Jack |title=FILM FANTASIES |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1995-06-18-9506180107-story.html |access-date=February 25, 2023 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=June 18, 1995}}</ref> Morgan also performed many of Spears's popular songs in her concerts, including "[[Silver Wings and Golden Rings]]".<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Jessen |first1=Wade |title=Country Corner |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=December 23, 1995 |page=48 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nQ0EAAAAMBAJ&dq=billie+jo+spears+standing+tall+lorrie+morgan+1995&pg=PA48 |access-date=February 25, 2023}}</ref>

==Personal life and death==
Spears was married a total of five times.<ref name="Music Row"/><ref name="NY Times"/><ref name="Guardian"/> Dates of Spears's marriages and divorces have not been published. However, several of her spouses names have appeared in books. ''The Insider's Country Music Handbook'' reported that Spears was briefly married and divorced from both Terry Bethel and Doug Walton. Both were country music musicians.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Flint |first1=Joseph H. |last2=Nelson |first2=Judy A. |title=The Insider's Country Music Handbook |date=1993 |publisher=[[Gibbs Smith]] |isbn=978-0879055639 |page=312}}</ref> The book ''Grassroots Music in the Upper Cumberland'' reported a brief marriage to Mike Edlin, another fellow musician.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Lynwood Montell |editor1-first=William |title=Grassroots Music in the Upper Cumberland |date=2006 |publisher=[[University of Tennessee|University of Tennessee Press]] |isbn=978-1572335455 |page=16}}</ref> ''Finding Her Voice: This History of Women in Country Music'' explained that Spears married her third husband in 1975, who was fifteen years younger than she. His name was not given. Spears spoke of the age difference in the book, "I guess I just think young. If it was the other way around, no one would give it a second thought...You're only as young as you feel."{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=357}} From her various marriages, Spears had three children: Tim Pierce, Kevin Jones and Ronnie Jones.<ref name="NY Times"/>

In the early 1970s, it was discovered that Spears had nodules on her vocal cords. She underwent two surgeries and had to spend six months in silence so her voice could recover.<ref name="Gulf Coast">{{cite web |title=Billie Jo Spears |url=https://www.museumofthegulfcoast.org/billie-jo-spears |website=[[Museum of the Gulf Coast]] |access-date=March 11, 2023}}</ref> "I was singing too high and straining on the high notes. It took six months of total silence to recover. I lowered all my keys and I don't scream anymore," she said.<ref name="Independent"/> In 1980, Spears was injured in a car accident in Nashville, Tennessee. ''Billboard'' reported that she suffered a concussion, a fractured arm and multiple cuts. She was hospitalized for one day and had to cancel several concert engagements. However, she made a full recovery.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Newsbreaks: Billie Jo Spears Hurt in Crash |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=September 13, 1980 |page=54 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jiQEAAAAMBAJ&dq=billie+jo+spears+outlaw+woman&pg=PT53 |access-date=March 11, 2023}}</ref> In 1993, she underwent [[Coronary artery bypass surgery|triple bypass heart surgery]] and made a full recovery.<ref>{{cite web |title=Billie Jo Spears Dead at 73 |url=https://theboot.com/billie-joe-spears-dead/ |website=The Boot |date=December 14, 2011 |access-date=March 11, 2023}}</ref>

A heavy smoker, Spears suffered from lung cancer in her final years. In her autobiography, singer and friend Philomena Begley spoke of how Spears became increasingly weaker and frail shortly before her death. Begley also said that Spears continued to smoke despite her diagnosis.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Begley |first1=Philomena |title=Philomena Begley My Life, My Music, My Memories |date=2017 |publisher=[[The O'Brien Press]] |isbn=978-1847179876 |chapter=7: Texas to Tyrone: Me and Billie Jo}}</ref> Spears chose to spend her final days in [[hospice]] care at her home in [[Vidor, Texas]].<ref name="Beaumont Enterprise"/> On December 14, 2011, she died at her Vidor home at the age of 73.<ref name="NY Times"/>

